<li id="c11">
  <div class="cx" id="cx50880450">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">income inequality</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1226678/50880450#c11?mode=alone;showrate=1#c11">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Raising minimum wages will simply increase unemployment among low skilled workers.</p>
<p>Income inequality is the result of globalization. &nbsp;Elizabeth Warren asked the right question when she asked what the minimum wage would be today if it tracked US productivity growth the past 30 years or so-the answer: $14.10. &nbsp;Why is it not at this point? &nbsp;Global competition.</p>
<p>It is not some Republican conspiracy, after all, no one was a bigger free trade guy than Bill Clinton.</p>
<p>Cheaper wages and huge productivity gains by other countries, i.e. China, have forced wages in low skilled industries to converge. &nbsp;In China's case, they have gone up and in the higher wage US, down.</p>
<p>The effects of globalization are so great that even 100% tax rates on the rich would not close a) our budget deficit or b) reduce inequality by very much (like Britain in the 70's, rich people's wealth would leave the country).</p>
<p>The solution to income inequality is not some clunky government program but job training and a lot of it. &nbsp; We simply must have the work force to do higher value added work. &nbsp;I would vote any day for more government sponsored job training.</p>
<p>One more thing. &nbsp;Why would anyone who is worried about income inequality-me-ever, ever vote for immigration reform? &nbsp;This is the worse piece of legislation for the poor that I can think of.<br /></p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:75627">toddleem</a> on <a href="/comments/1226678/50880450#c11">Sun Jul 28, 2013 at 05:40:41 PM PDT</a></p>
